## 🚀 Deployment (Experimental)

This guide will help you deploy the Habit Tracker application to production. The app consists of a React frontend, a Node.js/Express backend, and a MongoDB database.

### Prerequisites

- MongoDB Atlas account (for cloud database)
- Heroku account (for backend deployment)
- Netlify account (for frontend deployment)
- Git

### 1. Prepare the Application for Production

#### Backend Configuration

First, update the server to use environment variables:

1. Install dotenv:
   ```bash
   cd server
   npm install dotenv
   ```

2. Create a `.env` file in the `server` directory:
   ```
   MONGO_URI=mongodb+srv://<username>:<password>@cluster.mongodb.net/habit-tracker?retryWrites=true&w=majority
   PORT=5000
   ```

3. Update `server/server.js`:
   ```javascript
   import express from "express";
   import mongoose from "mongoose";
   import cors from "cors";
   import dotenv from "dotenv";
   import habitRoutes from "./routes/habits.js";

   dotenv.config();

   const app = express();
   app.use(cors());
   app.use(express.json());

   mongoose.connect(process.env.MONGO_URI || "mongodb://127.0.0.1:27017/habit-tracker")
     .then(() => console.log("MongoDB connected"))
     .catch(err => console.error(err));

   app.use("/api/habits", habitRoutes);

   const PORT = process.env.PORT || 5000;
   app.listen(PORT, () => console.log(`Server running on port ${PORT}`));
   ```

#### Frontend Configuration

Update the frontend to use environment variables for the API URL:

1. In `client/src/App.jsx`, add at the top:
   ```javascript
   const API_BASE = import.meta.env.VITE_API_BASE_URL || 'http://localhost:5000';
   ```

2. Replace all axios calls to use `API_BASE`:
   - `axios.get("http://localhost:5000/api/habits")` → `axios.get(`${API_BASE}/api/habits`)`
   - And similarly for POST, PUT, DELETE.

3. Do the same in `client/src/components/HabitForm.jsx` and `client/src/components/HabitList.jsx`.

### 2. Setup MongoDB Atlas

1. Create a new cluster on [MongoDB Atlas](https://www.mongodb.com/atlas)
2. Create a database user and whitelist your IP (or 0.0.0.0/0 for all)
3. Get the connection string and update your `.env` file

### 3. Deploy Backend to Heroku

1. Create a new app on [Heroku](https://www.heroku.com)
2. Connect your GitHub repository
3. Set environment variables in Heroku dashboard:
   - `MONGO_URI`: Your MongoDB Atlas connection string
   - `PORT`: 5000 (or leave default)
4. Enable automatic deploys or deploy manually
5. Your backend will be available at `https://your-app-name.herokuapp.com`

### 4. Deploy Frontend to Netlify

1. Create a new site on [Netlify](https://www.netlify.com)
2. Connect your GitHub repository and set build command to `npm run build`
3. Set publish directory to `dist`
4. Add environment variable:
   - `VITE_API_BASE_URL`: `https://your-heroku-app.herokuapp.com`
5. Deploy the site
6. Your frontend will be available at `https://your-netlify-site.netlify.app`

### 5. Update CORS (Optional)

If you encounter CORS issues, update the backend CORS configuration:

```javascript
app.use(cors({
  origin: 'https://your-netlify-site.netlify.app',
  credentials: true
}));
```

### 6. Test the Deployment

- Visit your Netlify URL
- Try creating, completing, and deleting habits
- Check that data persists in MongoDB Atlas

For more advanced deployments, consider using Docker or services like Railway/Render for unified deployment.